The 47-year-old daughter of Methodist ministers first ran for governor of Georgia in 2018, a race she lost by 55,000 votes.Her loss was attributed to wanton voter suppression in Georgia, that is, deliberate laws and efforts to ensure that a certain portion of the population (mostly blacks, Latinos and Asian-Americans) did not vote. As the US political temperatures reach an all-time high with post-election violence that saw Pro-Trump supporters breach the Capitol on Wednesday, history was being made in the state of Georgia.
Georgia, a state that was traditionally Republican formally turned Blue, first by voting for Joe Biden in the presidential race and then electing two democrats to senate, Rev Raphael Warnock and Jon Ossoff in a tight race that conjured up memories of the November presidential election.



