In the midst of this historic moment, one woman’s name keeps coming up — Stacey Abrams — the person who made all this possible and the one woman who entirely deserves all the credit. Stacey is an African American organiser and currently the most influential American not in elected office.
The 47-year-old daughter of Methodist ministers first ran for governor of Georgia in 2018, a race she lost by 55,000 votes. Her loss was attributed to wanton voter suppression in Georgia, that is, deliberate laws and efforts to ensure that a certain portion of the population (mostly blacks, Latinos and Asian-Americans) did not vote.



